CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a programming language used to style HTML elements. 
It defines how the content of a web page is presented, including layout, colors,
fonts, and spacing. CSS is used to create visually appealing and consistent web pages.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Example</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Hello, world!</h1>
    <p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>
</body>
</html>
body {
    background-color: lightblue;
}

h1 {
    color: red;
    font-size: 36px;
}

p {
    color: green;
    font-size: 18px;
}

Explanation of CSS Code
Selectors: The selectors body, h1, and p target specific HTML elements.

body: Selects the entire body of the HTML document.
h1: Selects all elements with the <h1> tag.
p: Selects all elements with the <p> tag.
Declarations: The declarations within the curly braces specify the styles 
to be applied to the selected elements.

background-color: Sets the background color of the body to light blue.
color: Sets the text color of the <h1> and <p> elements to red and green, respectively.
font-size: Sets the font size of the <h1> and <p> elements to 36px and 18px, respectively.
Effect on HTML Elements
The body element will have a light blue background.
The <h1> element will have red text and a font size of 36px.
The <p> element will have green text and a font size of 18px.